<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Rothmans to cut 1,000 jobs in Europe: Cigarette maker makes
Pounds 124m provision for rationalisation as profits fall to Pounds 344m for
year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rothmans International, the restructured tobacco group now shorn of its
Dunhill luxury goods interests, is to cut 1,000 jobs in Europe in a further
rationalisation of cigarette manufacturing.
The company is providing Pounds 123.8m to cover the pre-tax cost of the
moves, which involve the closure of factories in Berlin and The Hague and
rationalisation in Belgium.
The provisions resulted in a sharp fall in profits from Pounds 470.7m to
Pounds 343.6m for the year to March. Excluding the provisions and the Pounds
31.2m pre-tax costs of last year's group restructuring, profits rose 6 per
cent to Pounds 498.6m, with the increase entirely accounted for by exchange
rate movements.
Mr Bill Ryan, chief executive, said the closures were part of a long process
of rationalising acquisitions made after the war. 'In the mid-1970s we had
15 factories in Europe. When this is completed we will have six which is
still more than our main competitors.' Most of the job losses will result
from the closure of the Berlin factory. Production will be transferred to
Zevenaar in the Netherlands and to the two UK factories.
Rothmans had another difficult year in Europe with operating profits falling
23 per cent to Pounds 99.6m on slightly lower sales of Pounds 1.04bn (Pounds
1.08bn). Sales were down sharply in France, after a fierce price war, and by
more than 15 per cent in the UK, largely because two Budgets fell into the
period.
Mr Ryan said the rate of decline in Europe had slowed and he was now more
optimistic. 'We believe there may well be an improvement in the current year
with signs of economies picking up in Germany and France.'
Group operating profits rose 5 per cent to Pounds 438.7m, including an
additional Pounds 22.5m (Pounds 22.2m) of rationalisation costs on net sales
revenue 3 per cent higher at Pounds 2.49bn. Worldwide cigarette volumes fell
8 per cent.
The operating profits were less than the City had expected but net
investment income of Pounds 59.9m (Pounds 51.7m) was rather better. This
rise, which was despite the Pounds 450m special dividend paid last November,
partly reflected gains on the disposal of a securities portfolio.
Cash generation was also stronger than forecast with net liquid funds
falling only Pounds 252.4m to Pounds 665.1m after working capital was almost
halved to Pounds 204.1m.
Earnings per unit, excluding exceptional costs, edged up to 35.1p (34.6p)
and the dividend is 13.2p, up from a pro forma 11.5p.
Rothmans' strongest growth continues to come from Asia where profits jumped
37 per cent to Pounds 110.7m on sales of Pounds 408.5m (Pounds 318.4m). The
Americas contributed Pounds 90.4m (Pounds 85.5m) and the Pacific Pounds
52.7m (Pounds 46.4m).
Mr Nyren Scott Malden, of brokers BZW, edged down his current year forecast
by Pounds 15m to Pounds 525m. That puts the shares at 369p, down 9p, on a
forward multiple of just over 10 with a yield of 4.5 per cent.
</TEXT>
