<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Patten's job at risk in the wake of apology for 'nutter'
slur
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Patten, education secretary, yesterday faced Tory backbench calls
for his dismissal after he was faced with paying almost Pounds 100,000 in
settlement and costs for calling Professor Tim Brighouse, Birmingham's chief
education officer, a 'nutter'.
Many Conservative MPs privately urged the minister to resign before the
prime minister's forthcoming cabinet reshuffle, describing his remarks as
'deeply embarrassing' and lacking judgment.
While the Department for Education said Mr Patten had no intention of going
voluntarily, he is now expected to be a casualty of the ministerial
reshuffle.
Mr Patten must pay the legal costs and damages - which were not revealed but
were estimated by those close to Prof Brighouse at Pounds 100,000 - out of
his personal resources.
Neither the department nor the Conservative party will pay the damages, as
he made his original comments while speaking in a personal capacity. The
department said it did not know whether Mr Patten had any insurance to help
meet the claim. Mr Tony Newton, leader of the Commons, described the
incident as 'a private matter'.
The remarks came in a fringe meeting at last year's Conservative party
conference. In answer to questions from the floor, Mr Patten described Mr
Brighouse as a nutter and a madman who threatened to cause damage to
education in Birmingham as he already had in Oxfordshire.
Mr Patten was yesterday left with few friends in the Commons. An officer of
the 1922 committee summed up the mood of many Conservative MPs when he
described the incident 'as the final nail in Mr Patten's coffin'. He added:
'He should go now; but if he does not the Whips have been told in no
uncertain terms that he has lost all support from the backbenchers.'
The apology is unreserved, and with few, if any, recent precedents for a
secretary of state. The statement read in court said: 'Mr Patten now
recognises that his remarks were false and without any justification
whatsoever', and that he recognised Mr Brighouse's competence, integrity and
dedication.
Adding to black marks, Page 13
</TEXT>
