<DATE>940624
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Personal View: Dilemma over charges lies downstream
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID KINNERSLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In just four weeks, the UK water industry regulator, Ofwat, will reveal its
decision on allowed price increases for individual water companies. The
publicity surrounding current price negotiations for the 31 water utilities
of England and Wales has overshadowed a far more important issue which
customers and companies should be addressing - the basis on which charges
are actually calculated.
The main preoccupation so far has been with the 'K factors' - the rate above
inflation by which water companies will be allowed to increase water and
sewerage charges over the next five to 10 years. As the increases are to be
applied annually, more than 300 figures will be published by Ofwat in one
day.
The K factors are regarded as important primarily for company planners and
City analysts, who try to make forecasts for future profits of the
individual companies.
Yet the basis of calculation is equally significant, and has not been
consistently addressed.
Water companies have long depended on the old rating system as a
second-hand, low-cost way of fixing water bills for 18m households. However,
time is running out. The former UK prime minister, the then Mrs Margaret
Thatcher, was determined to replace the old rates system - which based water
bills on property values - with the poll tax. As part of the poll tax
programme, her government in 1988 passed a law making it illegal to base
water bills on any system derived from old rateable values after the year
2000. This means that water companies have just five more years to come up
with new ways of charging customers.
The privatised companies have been reluctant to face such troublesome
changes or to give up such an easy way of getting much of their income. Less
than 10 per cent of bills have been put on any new basis so far. Some 16m
households must be reviewed in the next five years.
The debate over what is the best method to calculate charges rages, even as
the price increases are being set.
A few companies see metering as the way forward, but want to stretch out the
change, and fear the heavy cost. Some who favour metering also argue that it
could penalise those who can least afford price increases  - for example,
large families in small houses, versus small families in large houses.
Others still hope to climb aboard the council tax system, much as they rode
on the back of the rates system. But council tax is riddled with rebates and
exemptions, which companies will not want to concede. The water industry
will not be allowed to pick the parts of the system that suit it.
The oddest idea being considered is a flat-rate licence fee in some areas,
bringing large increases or reductions in bills, still quite unrelated to
usage.
The essence of a utility is that it should be paid according to the volume
of its service to customers. This is in line with the National Rivers
Authority's insistence that water resources need to be conserved in some
parts of England, and new charging methods could and should promote that.
Meanwhile, the main focus is likely to remain on the more immediately
understandable K factor discussions. These are not as simple as they first
appear. The procedures have several faults. Most importantly, customers have
little idea of what goes into the pricing decisions: for example, how much
of the price increases are to finance future investment and so forth. There
is also no certainty over the rate of price increase - even with the K
factor - since nobody can accurately predict inflation.
Perhaps a greater fault is that this procedure over-dramatises the work of
Ofwat. Companies are already paying too much attention to its heavyweight
style of regulation. This could further isolate customers, who still worry
about water quality, dirty rivers and polluted beaches, as well as about
future water bills.
Neither the water company managements nor City analysts should make too much
of Ofwat's July decisions. Their worry should be that, as the companies
invest in providing better services, they have yet to settle a long-term way
of calculating bills and gathering money from domestic customers. They have
only five years to solve this problem and, more important, to explain their
solution to the customers.
The author is a former research fellow of Nuffield College Oxford and one of
several advisers to Mr Nicholas Ridley, secretary of state at the time of
water privatisation. His book 'Coming Clean' will be published by Penguin in
July
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9631 Regulation, Administration of Utilities.
    P4941 Water Supply.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>COSTS  Service costs &amp; Service prices.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
