FT  24 JUN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There are three World Cup soccer matches this evening. BBC2 shows Brazil v.
Cameroon at 8.30, and ITV shows Sweden v. Russia at 11.40. But the game that
will presumably attract most attention in the UK, now that the Irish have
beaten the Italians and been appointed honorary Brits, is Mexico v. Republic
of Ireland on ITV. Unfortunately for those with normal jobs and travel
arrangements, coverage starts at 5.15. Another outside broadcast on radio
comes from Glastonbury where John Peel is covering the summer music festival
(10.00 Radio 1). Channel 4 Goes To Glastonbury at 11.50 for more than two
hours of music. The names of the groups become more weird and wonderful
every year. Those playing today should include Madder Rose, Spin Doctors and
Manic Street Preachers. Of course soccer is not the only sport on television
today. Coverage of the Wimbledon championships begins on BBC2 at noon and
continues on BBC1 (1.50). There is another two and a half hours of live
coverage on BBC2 at 5.55, and then BBC1 screens highlights at 10.25.
