<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Technology (Worth Watching): Energy traders get integrated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Oil and gas traders, who have had to work with a proliferation of on-line
information sources, can now combine them all in a single PC-based
workstation. Saladin, a UK-based energy information company, this week
launched Crusader, a software product designed to integrate real-time market
sources and prices with historical data on one terminal.
Integration in this way offers two main advantages. First, the trader's
office becomes physically less cluttered. And second, the combined terminal
can carry out data analysis, including forecasts of future price movements,
which would be much more difficult with individual sources.
Similar software exists to integrate the mainstream financial information
sources, but Saladin says that energy trading stands out for the sheer
number of different sources available.
Crusader will cost about Pounds 2,000 a month for a five-user system.
Saladin: UK, 0932 243233.
</TEXT>
