<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Property spending up in first quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK pension funds and insurance companies invested a net Pounds 479m in
property in the first quarter of 1994, underlining the resurgence in the
commercial property market.
Figures from the Department of Trade and Industry show that net investment
in the first three months of the year was more than 90 per cent of the total
net investment in 1993, which was Pounds 520m.
The biggest spenders in the first quarter were long-term insurance funds,
which spent a net Pounds 537m. Other insurance funds sold a net Pounds 168m,
while pension funds invested a net Pounds 110m. The institutions were active
sellers as well as buyers, with sales of Pounds 1.35bn, compared with
purchases of Pounds 1.83bn.
They became enthusiastic buyers of property in the last quarter of 1993,
when they invested a net Pounds 791m, because they considered that property
values had hit bottom and offered good value compared with other
investments.
In the autumn of 1993 and the spring of 1994, the fierce competition to buy
prime property regularly pushed prices well above the asking price. However,
since Easter the market has cooled. Total returns from the property market
edged downwards in May, according to Richard Ellis, chartered surveyors.
Intense buying activity in the first half of the year has given way to a
quieter second half, as turbulence in the bond market spilled over into the
property market. The bond market's influence is because, in the absence of
rental growth, property resembles a fixed-interest investment.
Pressures from the bond market have particularly affected sales of buildings
that had little prospect of rental growth. Investors are giving more
consideration to the location and quality of a building, which will
determine rental growth.
Mr Adrian White of Fletcher King said: 'Investors must be convinced of the
underlying fundamentals of location and quality of a building, because the
yields now being achieved demand rent growth in the medium term to justify
acquisition against a background of higher bond yields.'
</TEXT>
