<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Disc-based travel planner launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Travellers in the north-west of England will be able to plan bus and train
journeys on their home computers following the launch of a journey planner
on a disc by Cumbria County Council.
The computer programme helps find the most convenient journey by giving
departure, arrival and connecting times for trips within the county and to
main destinations outside, such as Manchester and Glasgow.
The council hopes the Pounds 2.50 disc will be used by information centres,
libraries, bus operators and hotels as well as local people and visitors
with access to a computer.
The programme lists 980 destinations and includes the timetables of more
than 80 local transport operators. If the initial scheme is successful the
council plans to update the disc every six months for the public and monthly
for commercial organisations. The pilot scheme has cost Pounds 8,000.
Further refinements may include allowances for road works and diversions,
estimated walking times in town centres and between railway platforms, and
details of bus boarding points.
The Cumbrian disc is the first in the UK to include both train and bus
timetables. British Rail has produced a disc of its nationwide timetables
for the two past years, which sells about 4,000 copies at each six-monthly
update, mainly to large companies. Individual copies cost Pounds 41 or
Pounds 45 depending on the system used.
Disc-based journey planners are used by the railways in the Netherlands,
Norway, Finland and Denmark, and by two Danish bus companies. A disc
covering all forms of public transport is available in the Netherlands.
</TEXT>
