<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / MP warns on regional aid cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The long-term future of international companies' plants in England may be
jeopardised if the government cuts the regional aid it offers them to
upgrade their facilities, Mr Doug Henderson, Labour MP for Newcastle North,
warned yesterday.
Mr Henderson said a foreign-owned company with a plant in his constituency
had approached him for help after being told by the Department of Trade and
Industry in the past week that its application for Regional Selective
Assistance had been rejected.
He said the benefits of attracting international companies making products
for worldwide markets could be undermined if they found that further
investment, needed to maintain a competitive edge, did not win government
backing.
He has told the DTI of his concerns and will next week table parliamentary
questions, asking if the government is seeking to cut its regional aid
budget. He said: 'If companies like the one in my constituency feel they are
not getting the regional support they did in the past, and the support they
could get in other European countries, they will be less inclined to invest
in the future and that could mean jobs will be undermined.'
On Wednesday, the DTI confirmed that it was tightening the allocation of RSA
grants for projects in England, as part of public spending constraints. It
was also placing greater emphasis on the quality of jobs the projects would
create.
The clampdown, which affects foreign investors and indigenous companies, is
causing concern among economic regeneration bodies.
Mr Henderson said the company in his constituency, which he declined to
name, had received RSA in the past. It is understood it was seeking a
seven-figure sum this time. The proposed investment included equipment
modernisation and increased research and development.
The company was a world leader in its field, yet had been told its project
showed insufficient regard for skilling and high technology. The MP said the
company had told him an estimated 30 companies in north-east England had
been rejected for RSA recently.
The DTI said it could not comment on individual applications on grounds of
commercial confidentiality.
</TEXT>
