<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / KPMG points to growth of fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
International fraudsters are increasingly laundering money through physical
assets such as gold bars, senior fraud investigators claimed yesterday.
In an effort to prevent money flows being traced, they are buying precious
metals, antiques and other commodities, said Mr David Smith, a partner with
KPMG Peat Marwick's forensic accounting department.
Speaking at the opening of the department's annual conference, Mr Smith said
the transactions were partly a response to tougher guidelines on money
laundering. Much of the money came from drug transactions.
Mr Robert Chambers, head of the department, said there was a substantial
growth in fraud in the US, partly due to the loss of internal controls as
companies restructure during the recession.
He said there was evidence of growing involvement in corporate fraud by
organised crime, and that many police departments no longer had the budgets
to investigate white-collar crime.
Mr Smith said the development of high-quality colour photocopiers and
sophisticated printing equipment was making forgery difficult to detect.
He added that there was evidence of growing fraud in the former Soviet bloc,
particularly involving the Mafia, but that there was little government money
available to help pay for investigators to prevent fraud or recover stolen
money.
There was also a likelihood of growth in illegal money flows out of Hong
Kong and South Africa over the next few years, a reflection of the
countries' political instability.
He said it was important that companies ensured their employees took
holidays and others did their work while they were away, in an effort to
ensure that no frauds were being concealed by staff.
However, it is proving far easier than many believe to freeze assets held in
Switzerland, he said.
</TEXT>
