<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Study urges state funding of all 'off the job' training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
All 'off the job' vocational training leading to qualifications should be
paid for from public funds, a study from the London School of Economics
says.
Mr Ken Mahew, one of the editors of the study, said yesterday it was
difficult to cost the proposal but it could add Pounds 1bn to Pounds 2bn a
year to what the government spends on vocational training.
The UK is good at graduate training level, the report says, but increasingly
bad at lower levels of skill. 'In order to combat unemployment and low pay,
the top priority is to lift the skills of the less able workers.' The report
says this would not happen adequately through more people staying on in
full-time education. It required a system which guaranteed part-time
vocational education to everyone who did not stay on full-time.
The study also proposes:
Anyone employed aged under 19 should be employed as a trainee - with clear
obligations on the employer, and appropriate levels of pay.
Any company employing workers under 19 should by law ensure they receive at
least one day a week off-the-job vocational education.
A review of National Vocational Qualifications.
Funding to be through existing channels.
Britain's Training Deficit: The Centre for Economic Performance. Mr Richard
Layard, Mr Ken Mahew and Sir Geoffrey Owen.
</TEXT>
