<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Racal offshoot escapes action
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A subsidiary of Racal Electronics, the UK data communications and network
services group, has escaped legal action from the Office of Fair Trading
after giving assurances on its policy for supplying equipment to dealers.
The OFT said yesterday that Racal Health and Safety had given the assurances
to Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, after notice of his
intention to start legal action under the 1976 Resale Prices Act.
The company is a leading UK manufacturer of respiratory equipment and the
world's biggest producer of powered respirators.
The case arose after Protec (Manchester), a distributor of industrial
protective equipment, complained to the OFT last summer. Sir Bryan
subsequently alleged that the Racal company had breached the act by
threatening to refuse to supply Protec because it was giving excessive
discounts.
The act makes it unlawful for a supplier to withhold goods if they are sold
below a specified price, or to notify dealers of a price stated, or
calculated to be understood, as a minimum price.
The Racal offshoot has assured Sir Bryan that it was not company policy to
notify minimum prices to its customers and that it would not contravene the
act.
Sir Bryan said yesterday: 'I take breaches of the Resale Prices Act very
seriously. I am glad that in this case supplies to Protec were not
interrupted.
'It is important that all of Racal's distributors should know that in the
pursuit of profitability they are free to sell, advertise and display for
sale products from Racal and other suppliers at whatever price they choose.'
The OFT said legal action in such cases was very rare, and most cases were
settled after assurances from the company against which the complaint had
been made.
Protec said last night that the threat of legal action by Sir Bryan had
helped secure the future of Protec Direct, its discount direct mail
operation.
Mr Jonathan Prest, managing director of Protec, said: 'The success of Protec
Direct has proved that the market is looking for established brand name
products at low prices.'
</TEXT>
