<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / CBI reports upward price pressures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The industrial recovery remains on track but growing numbers of
manufacturers expect to raise prices in the next four months, the latest
Confederation of British Industry monthly industrial trends survey shows.
The survey, published today, says companies' price expectations rose in
June, after several months in which price expectations have been fairly
flat.
Twenty-one per cent of companies questioned hope to increase domestic prices
in the next four months, while only 9 per cent expect to reduce them.
This positive balance of 12 per cent on the question of raising prices is
significantly higher than in the months between February and May, when the
balance ranged between minus 1 per cent and plus 4 per cent.
The CBI pointed out yesterday, however, that company expectations could be
overly optimistic - when the balance of price expectations last rose to 12
per cent in January these expectations were largely unrealised.
Although the City is watching closely for any sign that the economic
recovery could be fuelling inflationary pressures, Mr Howard Davies, CBI
director-general, yesterday denied that the figures were a cause for alarm.
He said: 'The outlook for inflation is less positive than last month . . .
but we cannot yet be sure that this signals a change from the subdued
inflation outlook of recent surveys.'
Mr Davies added: 'Companies are still facing tough competitive conditions in
both home and export markets and overall inflationary pressures remain low.'
Elsewhere, the survey, which questioned 1,124 companies representing about
half of UK manufacturing, paints a picture of steady, modest growth.
Order books remained at their best levels for five years with 28 per cent of
companies believing that business is 'below normal', while only 25 per cent
believe it is 'better than normal'.
The balance in these total orders between export-driven and domestic demand
was stable - suggesting that April's tax increases have not significantly
dented domestic demand.
Export order books were unchanged, at their best level for four years - 27
per cent of companies said exports were above normal, while 29 per cent said
they were below.
</TEXT>
