<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Accounting move may help small companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hundreds of thousands of smaller companies may escape the requirement to
follow existing accounting standards, under radical proposals being drawn up
by the profession.
Preliminary recommendations to exempt smaller companies from certain
standards were drawn up by a working party created by the Accounting
Standards Board. They were announced at the annual conference of the
Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales held in London
yesterday.
The findings follow widespread calls that generally accepted accounting
principles are primarily drawn up forbig companies but must also be followed
by smaller companies.
Under existing practice, all of the UK's 1m limited companies must obey the
accounting rules laid down in law and produced by the board, although many
are less relevant and more costly for smaller companies to follow.
Ms Danielle Stewart, a partner with Warrener Stewart and a member of the
working party, said: 'Financial reporting is all about communication, and I
do not believe the communication value of small or private company accounts
is improved by the addition of a myriad of disclosure requirements and
complex accounting treatments.'
She argued that compliance with accounting standards could only be justified
when in the public interest - which meant they should apply only to quoted
companies or others with substantial public interest.
Smaller companies believed the requirement to comply with accounting
standards often made their accounts more unintelligible, she said.
The working party, which was set up under the auspices of the Consultative
Committee of Accountancy Bodies, representing the leading six professional
bodies, is still considering the threshold below which companies would be
exempt.
</TEXT>
