<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / BR chiefs angered by signals row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Rail chiefs are furious about what they see as the incompetent
handling of the signalling staff's dispute by Railtrack, the state-owned
company responsible since April 1 for maintaining the railway network.
It emerged yesterday that senior BR managers believe they could have reached
an agreement with the RMT rail union over the grievances of the signalling
staff last year.
They say they were unable to do so because Railtrack insisted on taking over
responsibility for negotiating a deal with the signalling staff in April
last year rather than on the company's vesting day on April 1 this year.
The BR managers said that by spring last year they were at an advanced stage
in a study of the restructuring of the pay and conditions of the signalling
staff with the support of RMT union - a process that started in August 1991.
Railtrack took over the signalling staff issue on April 22 last year.
British Rail said it could not understand why there was such a long delay at
Railtrack before the package of restructuring proposals for signalling staff
was put to the RMT jointly with BR last November.
Meanwhile, the independent Public Finance Foundation yesterday released
figures suggesting that railway signalling staff have had among the lowest
increases in earnings of any public sector group in the past five years.
Since 1988 their earnings have risen by an average of 43 per cent, compared
with 44 per cent for local government workers, 56 per cent for the police,
51 per cent for the armed forces, 48 per cent for health service employees
and 52 per cent for those in education.
Only civil servants - at 42 per cent - have had smaller rises over the
period. Employees in the private sector had average rises of 53 per cent in
the past six years.
Mr Chris Trinder, head of the Public Finance Foundation, said: 'The railway
signalling staff failed to benefit from the pre-general election pay bonanza
of 1991-1992.'
But signalling staff are also the last group of workers on the railway
network not to have benefited from job restructuring that started in 1990.
Their position looks particularly anomalous compared with the signal and
telecommunication technicians and supervisors grade immediately above them
in the hierarchy.
That group acquired a new pay structure in 1992 that improved basic pay
rates by 25 per cent with a shorter working week in return for job
evaluation and work flexibility.
Other groups already covered by restructuring deals include Railfreight
distribution staff, retail and customer service staff and civil engineering
supervisors.
