<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Pensions - The White Paper: Qualified welcome from employers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER and LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Employers' organisations yesterday gave a qualified welcome to the
government's proposals for pension law reform, but the Trades Union Congress
described it as 'totally inadequate'.
Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the Confederation of British Industry,
said: 'The government has paid some attention to company representations and
has proposed a less burdensome regime than the Goode Committee advocated,
but one which nonetheless will improve security for occupational pension
scheme members.'
Mr John Monks, general secretary of the Trades Union Congress said: 'We were
looking for a tough package that would prevent employers ripping off their
employees' pensions, but employees still will not be assured of that basic
warranty.
'The framework in the white paper still would not prevent workers losing
their pension rights to pay the price of their employers' dishonesty.'
Employers' concerns focused on the costs of the proposed minimum solvency
standards and the compensation scheme to cover losses resulting from theft
or fraud.
The Institute of Directors said the government had clearly tried to strike a
balance between preventing another Maxwell episode and imposing heavy
burdens and costs on companies operating pension schemes.
But there was a price to pay for all new regulatory systems, and the
proposal could make companies more reluctant to operate schemes. The
definition of solvency and the precise application of the age rebates would
be crucial.
The CBI and the IoD were unhappy about the compensation scheme, and the
extent to which good schemes will have to pay for bad ones. The proposed
regulator and the compensation scheme should be financed by the government,
said the CBI, rather than by a levy on schemes.
The CBI said the obligation to maintain 100 per cent solvency, irrespective
of short-term stock market fluctuations, 'could provoke large-scale
switching from equities to gilts and, in the long run, reduce the returns
available to pensioners'.
The Engineering Employers Federation welcomed the phasing in of solvency
standards, and the strengthening of the role of pension fund trustees. It
pointed out that training for all trustees, and not just member trustees,
was important.
Mr Monks criticised the government for ignoring calls for a majority of the
trustees to be elected by scheme members. 'Member trustees can play a vital
role in eliminating pension fund fraud. Under these proposals they still
will not comprise a majority on trustee boards,' he said.
Other criticisms came from Mr Roger Lyons, general secretary of the MSF, the
scientific and technical union, who said: 'Pension law reform was supposed
to protect pension scheme members against employers like Robert Maxwell. Far
from closing the stable door on pension abuse this white paper leaves it
propped open.'
Mr John Edmonds, general secretary of the GMB general union, said the white
paper had introduced a weak and ineffectual regulator without the necessary
enforcement powers.
</TEXT>
