<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Pensions - The White Paper: Insolvency risk remains serious
matter - Barry Riley discusses the implications for pension-fund investment
policies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The minimum solvency standard in the white paper is not quite as tough as
the one proposed last year by the Goode committee.
But the 90-day rule - that solvency of under 90 per cent must be corrected
through a cash injection or something similar within three months - will
mean companies still have to take the insolvency risk very seriously.
According to Ms Penny Webster of consulting actuaries Bacon &amp; Woodrow it is
also surprising that no smoothing of market values or interest rates is to
be permitted. A scheme that had an annual valuation on a particularly bad
day for the market could be forced into an injection which would not be
necessary on a broader view.
It has been argued by Mr Alistair Ross Goobey, head of the PosTel pension
fund management firm and a member of the Goode committee, that it could be a
blessing in disguise to be forced to invest at the bottom of the market. But
the threat of a cash hit in the middle of a national financial crisis is the
finance director's nightmare.
How might investment strategies be affected? The simple proposition is that
the holding of a significant proportion of low-risk assets, such as
short-dated bonds or index-linked gilts, will reduce the volatility of the
fund compared with a normal pension fund portfolio, which has more than 80
per cent in UK and overseas equities.
Therefore schemes with weak solvency will be prudent to buy lower-risk
investments, but this will also reduce the expected return. Over the past 30
years the total return on gilts has been on average 5.5 per cent a year less
than on UK equities. A high-gilt strategy would therefore involve
significantly larger regular contributions.
A complicating factor is that the maturity of many UK pension schemes,
especially the large ones, is rapidly increasing. Many have substantially
more pensioners and deferred pensioners on their books than current
employees. So their liabilities are becoming more predictable and can be
safely matched against fixed coupon or index-linked bonds, and are less
easily matched against equities.
On the other hand, this means that the concession compared with the Goode
version, that cash equivalents could be based on high equity returns - and
thus be much cheaper - for younger members, will be less beneficial in a
maturing environment.
There could thus be a double effect as the minimum solvency standard is
phased in over the next six or seven years. Figures released earlier this
week on the investment patterns of UK pension funds in the first quarter of
the year already showed sharply higher purchases of gilts - Pounds 3.3bn,
which was more than in the whole of last year.
Tentative figures in the white paper suggest that the extra gilts required
would be no more than Pounds 9bn.
Funds would not sell UK equities but would run their holdings of overseas
equities and bonds down by about Pounds 7.5bn instead, apparently because
foreign assets would offer a less safe match for UK liabilities. This would
be a comfortable outcome, posing no threat to the UK stock market and
promising a slightly - but not dramatically - easier environment for the
government to finance its deficits.
There is, however, a quite different argument based on the proposition that
it is highly risky for UK pension schemes to hold almost 60 per cent of
their assets in a single asset class (UK equities). Diversification will be
an imperative, and one that would require significantly greater holdings of
overseas assets, as well as gilts.
This could seriously threaten the UK equity market, of which UK pension
funds own about a third.
The government will play down the possibility of such a damaging strategic
upheaval, but the danger cannot be dismissed at this stage. There is no
getting away from the fact that providing effective insurance for schemes
against the impact of securities market disasters is going to cost employers
money. There may need to be further negotiations and adjustments before a
final deal is struck.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
    P6371 Pension, Health, and Welfare Funds.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government News.
    TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT942-1432</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EFXC1ACAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940624
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Pensions - The White Paper: Funds face asset allocation
changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The proposed minimum solvency standard is expected to have a significant
impact on the asset allocation of UK pension funds, reducing the average
fund's proportion of equities to as little as 50 per cent from the current
80 per cent to 85 per cent.
The schemes likely to be affected are those with a 'mature' membership -
schemes which have a disproportionate number of members who are either
already retired or very close to pension age. Schemes that are at or under
the minimum solvency level will also face considerable difficulties if the
proposed timescales for rectifying underfunding are not modified.
The main problem for average and mature schemes is that the long-term
funding for liabilities linked to earnings inflation - as is the case with
future pensions - demands a high equity exposure.
However, the way the solvency level is calculated assumes the company
becomes insolvent tomorrow and therefore the fund requires a much greater
proportion of gilts since these are used to match immediate pension
liabilities.
Consulting actuaries Bacon &amp; Woodrow estimated that in extreme
circumstances, where a scheme's liabilities related to a membership solely
comprised of pensioners, the fund could have to switch to 100 per cent in
gilts.
The average fund, which has one third of its membership already as
pensioners, could be forced to disinvest up to 30 per cent of its UK and
overseas equity portfolios.
Mr Richard Whitelam, partner with Bacon &amp; Woodrow, said: 'The matched
position for an average scheme with one-third pensioner liability is close
to 50-50 in equities and gilts. This compares with the current Combined
Actuarial Performance Services average distribution of close to 85 per cent
in equities and the remainder in gilts, bonds and cash.'
The impact on the equity markets cannot be gauged at this stage, but it
seems certain that the schemes most likely to be affected are also some of
the UK's largest. Former public sector companies and the heavy manufacturing
industries are the most obvious examples of mature schemes. The mineworkers
scheme, the steel and chemical industry funds, the merchant navy pension
funds and even some of the banks' schemes are considered very mature due to
the shedding of large numbers of staff during the recession and, in some
cases, the privatisation process. Several of these funds are valued in the
Pounds 12bn to Pounds 15bn range.
Where funds switch from equities to bonds the likely impact in reduced
annual returns is dramatic, as can be seen in the table. Mr Eric Lambert,
investment consultant at pension performance measurement company WM, said,
'Each additional 10 per cent of bond investment equates in broad terms to a
reduction in return of 0.3 per cent per annum over periods between 10 and 20
years. An increase of 30 per cent in bond investment could reduce
prospective returns by about 1 per cent per annum.'
Looking ahead, Mr Lambert said that the additional cost in terms of lost
investment opportunity after 20 years for an average UK pension fund of
Pounds 200m that had to switch to a portfolio structure of 50 per cent
equities and 50 per cent bonds would be Pounds 861m.
Mr Ross Russell, a partner with actuaries Hymans Robertson and a member of
the Association of Consulting Actuaries (ACA) pensions committee, said that
employers had an alternative option to switching wholesale out of equities.
'Employers could consider contributing more to the scheme to build up
surplus funds as a buffer against investment fluctuations and other adverse
experience.'
A second alternative, to use futures and options to protect against
investment fluctuations, was not workable because there was insufficient
capacity in the equity markets, he said.
Mr Russell added: 'The ACA's main concern is the tight timescales laid down
to rectify an insolvency position. This could mean that a company has to
make a huge cash injection or create yet another creditor to the company.
'However, despite the categorical wording in the white paper, we understand
that the government intends to seek further consultation on this issue and
we welcome this initiative.'
The government is also understood to be considering a new type of gilt that
would more closely match the future liabilities of schemes under the minimum
solvency standard.
