<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Pensions - The White Paper: Inflation-link guarantee to
disappear - Deborah Harrison on the 'double blow' proposed changes in the
administration of schemes may deal to consumers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In April 1997 the government will remove an important inflation-linked
guarantee - known as the guaranteed minimum pension or GMP - provided by the
majority of UK company pension schemes.
Experts say the change will simplify company scheme administration, but the
consumer will lose out. The measure will create a long-term net saving to
the Exchequer of Pounds 1.5bn in the year 2050.
The vast majority of final salary schemes in the UK contract the entire
scheme membership out of the State Earnings Related Pension Scheme (Serps)
and in return pay a reduced rate of National Insurance contribution.
They also have to guarantee to provide a replacement pension that is at
least the equivalent in value to Serps.
However, at present contracted-out members do not forfeit the entire Serps
pension but retain an element of inflation-linked top-up from the state
scheme.
This Serps-matching requirement is particularly valuable for early leavers
because the deferred Serps pension entitlement is increased each year in
line with earnings inflation, unlike most private schemes. Serps pensions
are based on 20 per cent to 25 per cent of NI 'band earnings' - that is,
earnings between Pounds 2,964 and Pounds 22,360 for the current tax year.
Personal pensions and group money purchase schemes contracted out of Serps,
which provide a pension based on investment returns rather than on the
individual's final salary, do not have to provide a GMP.
After 1997 final salary schemes will no longer have to provide the GMP in
order to contract members out of Serps. Instead there will be a general test
based on the 'overall quality of the total benefits offered' which, the
government said, 'should be superior to those offered in Serps'.
Ms Penny Webster, partner with actuarial consultants Bacon &amp; Woodrow, said:
'Scheme members will suffer a double blow. They will lose the valuable
top-up between the value of the GMP and the value of Serps that is currently
provided by the state scheme.
'They will also lose the full inflation-linking of the GMP, particularly
where it is deferred for early leavers.
'The government has simplified the system but at the expense of the
consumer.'
Ms Joanne Segars, pensions officer at the Trades Union Congress, said: 'In
light of (Robert) Maxwell and the personal pensions scandal, the government
should be taking the lead in providing more pension security, not weakening
it.'
The government said the change, which severs the link between contracted-out
occupational schemes and Serps, will simplify and speed up the move to equal
pensions for men and women - a requirement of European Union law.
GMPs are based on the value of Serps and therefore increase at a different
rate for men and women because men are able to draw the state pension at 65
and women at 60.
The white paper also changes the terms for the rebate of NI contributions
paid to contracted-out schemes.
The rebate is calculated as a percentage of band earnings and for the
current tax year is 4.8 per cent (5.4 per cent with tax relief). Those with
personal pensions, who are aged 30 or over, receive an extra 1 per cent.
The government said that all money purchase schemes would in future be
entitled to the bonus for older members but that final salary schemes will
continue to receive a flat-rate rebate.
Moreover, when the government actuary sets the new rebate level in 1997 it
is expected to be higher than the existing figure.
The government hopes this will encourage more people to opt out of Serps to
reduce the long-term financial pressure on the state scheme. The white paper
also introduces changes to improve the flexibility of personal pensions.
First, by extending the limited age-related rebate system the government
aims to make it attractive for employees of all ages to opt out of Serps
whether they have an individual personal pension or are members of a
contracted-out group money purchase scheme.
A second boost to personal pensions is the measure to give investors greater
flexibility over when they convert their investment into an annuity.
The measure would allow individuals to keep their pension fund fully
invested and to postpone the annuity purchase to any age up to 75, instead
of immediately on retirement as at present.
</TEXT>
