<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Clarke heads off calls to cut taxes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, yesterday put tax cuts on the back burner
by warning the cabinet that reductions in public spending would be
'extremely tough'.
Facing renewed rightwing calls for early tax cuts to restore Tory
popularity, Mr Clarke told ministers not to underestimate the difficulty of
achieving existing fore-casts.
Backed by Mr Michael Portillo, the chief secretary to the Treasury, Mr
Clarke said all the obvious targets for cuts had been tackled in last year's
public spending round.
The chancellor's warnings, delivered at the beginning of a one-hour debate
on public spending, forestalled any discussion of tax cuts by the cabinet's
rightwing minority.
The cabinet did not discuss undershooting the Treasury's 'control totals'
for non-cyclical spending of Pounds 263bn for the coming financial year and
Pounds 272.3bn for 1996-97.
Downing Street said spending would be kept 'within' the control totals,
renamed ceilings to emphasise the Treasury's view of them as limits rather
than targets.
Mr Clarke told the cabinet his strategy would keep growth of public spending
during the period to 1997 below growth in the economy as a whole. He said
the government remained committed to reducing the proportion of national
output taken by the state, which would, in turn, reduce the public sector
deficit.
Mr Clarke has said that he will not cut taxes until a looser fiscal stance
is justified by reductions in the public sector borrowing requirement. But
his remarks keep open the option of tax cuts in 1995 or 1996, which would
satisfy many backbenchers who believe tax will be the main issue in the next
general election.
In the City, analysts remained worried that ministers might be tempted into
tax cuts in an attempt to restore the government's declining popularity.
'If they can deliver spending cuts in 1994, they may be able to cut taxes in
1995,' said Mr Adrian Cooper, UK economist at James Capel. 'But we do need
to see actual cuts in spending rather than vague trimming of the contingency
reserve.'
Ms Harriet Harman, the shadow chief secretary, accused the government of
endangering Britain's long-term economic prospects by planning further cuts
in public investment.
'Cuts in public investment will simply exacerbate Britain's chronic economic
problems of under-investment and under-capacity,' she said.
Detailed analysis of the prospects for public spending cuts will be carried
out by the EDX committee, chaired by the chancellor, which will report to
the cabinet in the autumn.
The committee is expected to look hard at the scope for cuts in the Pounds
85bn social security budget, the criminal justice system and the running
costs of government departments.
</TEXT>
