<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / SFO wins test case on silence clause
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Serious Fraud Office yesterday won a test case over its powers to remove
a suspect's right to silence, John Mason writes.
Giving judgment after a judicial review, two High Court judges ruled that Mr
Larry Trachtenberg, one of six men charged over the Maxwell affair, had no
reasonable excuse when he refused to answer the SFO's questions during a
'section 2' interview.
Under section 2 of the Criminal Justice Act 1988 suspects are obliged to
answer questions put to them by SFO investigators unless they have a
reasonable excuse.
After his arrest in June 1992 Mr Trachtenberg, a former adviser to Robert
Maxwell, refused to answer questions and was charged with a breach of
section 2.
In February last year a stipendiary magistrate at Clerkenwell magistrates
court, London, ordered Mr Trachten-berg's acquittal, accepting his argument
that he had a reasonable excuse not to answer questions because he had
already been arrested and charged. The High Court judges yesterday
overturned the magistrate's ruling, saying his approach to the case had been
'fundamentally flawed'.
</TEXT>
