<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Music to the industry's ears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Monopoly situations exist in both the music production and retailing
industries, but neither operates against the public interest, the Monopolies
and Mergers Commission said yesterday.
The commission, which published its report on the UK music industry
yesterday, found that prices of compact discs in the UK were not excessive.
It said prices were 'set at levels determined by effective competition in
the UK market'.
The five leading music companies form a complex monopoly, it said, which
means that they engage in practices which prevent, restrict or distort
competition. The five - EMI, PolyGram, Sony, Warner and BMG - account for
about 70 per cent of the UK market.
Among the practices referred to by the commission are restrictions on
parallel imports, which allow music companies to block imports of their own
products from abroad.
The commission said lifting restrictions on parallel imports would be
contrary to the European Union rental directive and would increase the risk
of music piracy. It said it did not think freer imports of music would
result in lower prices. Some countries with no parallel import restrictions
had higher CD prices than the UK, it said.
The music companies' complex monopoly did not operate against the public
interest, the commission said. It added: 'The majors compete vigorously
amongst themselves and also with the independent sector, consisting of some
600 companies.'
The commission said that, in record retailing, WH Smith and its subsidiary
Our Price constitute a scale monopoly, as they supply more than a quarter of
the market.
However, it added that the WH Smith group, which accounts for 26.6 per cent
of UK music sales, operated in a competitive market and did not make
excessive music retailing profits.
The commission also said there was no case for changing the contracts
between artists and record companies. The commission said the proper forum
for resolving disputes between artists and companies was in the courts.
Pop singer George Michael failed this week in his attempt to get the High
Court to declare his contract with Sony unenforceable.
Nevertheless, the commission found that contracts have generally moved in
artists' favour during the past 20 years. It said advances and royalty rates
had increased and the length of contracts had come down.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
