<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / New Chiapas peace broker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Carlos Salinas has appointed Mr Jorge Madrazo, the head of the
government human rights commission, to be the new commissioner for peace in
the Mexican state of Chiapas, indicating a continuing commitment to a
negotiated settlement to the conflict.
Mr Salinas said Mr Madrazo would be entrusted with bringing a 'dignified
peace' to Chiapas. The appointment of the respected Mr Madrazo and President
Salinas's commitment to peaceful resolution follows rebel rejection of the
government peace offer nearly two weeks ago, and resignation of the previous
peace commissioner, Mr Manuel Camacho.
'This raises the possibility and expectation that dialogue can continue
despite the Zapatista rejection of the peace agreement,' said a government
official.
The Zapatista rebels seized four towns in the state of Chiapas on new year's
day. Although a ceasefire was reached in early January, the Zapatistas
remain armed. Still in control of a southern part of Chiapas, they have
threatened to rise up against the government and remain a threat to the
security of the state.
The call for dialogue may help reduce tension in the area, and should allay
fears of a government crackdown. However, Mr Salinas did not meet the
central Zapatista demand of agreeing to further national democratic reforms,
saying such reforms had been negotiated by the main political parties, and
without such a commitment, it seems unlikely an agreement can be reached.
</TEXT>
