<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Jobs warning to the Netherlands
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The next Dutch government must seize the opportunity of a mild economic
recovery to reform the Netherlands' rigid labour market, the Organisation
for Economic Co-operation and Development said in its survey published
yesterday.
The country's labour market is 'unquestionably the weak spot of an otherwise
fundamentally healthy economy', according to the OECD.
It said incentives to find work were low in the Netherlands, reflecting the
traditional generosity of the welfare state system. Other problems
identified by the OECD were high Dutch labour costs, stiff job protection
laws and wage-setting by economic sector which prevents prospective
employees from 'bidding' for lower wages.
'On balance, employment protection legislation seems to be detrimental to
employment,' it said.
The OECD, noting that growth of gross domestic product is projected to rise
to 2.75 per cent next year, said: 'The challenge to the next government is
to seize this opportunity, relying on the many strengths of the Dutch
economy and society, and to move towards major reforms now, rather than only
if and when it is faced with the threat of an impending crisis.'
</TEXT>
