<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / Tougher rules planned for pensions: Fraud prevention
targeted in white paper - Regulator would enforce standards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, JAMES BLITZ, and LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A far-reaching overhaul of the occupational pensions industry, with the
proposed creation of a regulator with powers to enforce common standards,
was unveiled by the government yesterday.
Its white paper was tougher than had been expected, endorsing many of the
proposals urged nine months ago by its own advisory panel, the Goode
Committee.
The paper also proposes that pension schemes meet minimum solvency
standards, allow members to appoint at least a third of their scheme's
trustees, and contribute to a compensation scheme that will pay pensions if
assets disappear through fraud.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, said the prevention of fraud was
at the heart of his proposals. He emphasised that no single measure could
provide a satisfactory defence against fraud, but claimed the new
arrangements could have prevented the Maxwell pensions scandal had they been
on the statute book some years ago.
Mr Lilley said his proposals would 'strengthen the whole pensions industry
by providing the three basic essentials of security, equality and choice'.
Industry reaction to the white paper was generally supportive, although
employers, scheme advisers and the pension industry's trade association all
expressed some reservations.
Industry professionals estimate pension schemes will have to spend 10 times
the Pounds 60m to Pounds 140m that the government says is needed to meet the
new standards. The Goode Committee was formed in June 1992 following the
death of Robert Maxwell and the subsequent discovery that more than Pounds
440m had disappeared from pension schemes he controlled.
The government proposes, however, that the regulator be less powerful than
suggested by the Goode Committee. It will have to rely largely on
'whistle-blowing' by professional advisers and scheme members to uncover
wrongdoing and will not routinely inspect scheme financial statements. Also,
contrary to recommendations that it be financed from general revenues, the
government proposes that a levy on industry finances a budget of about
Pounds 10m.
Labour criticised the white paper as failing to ensure the regulator would
be independent.
Mr Frank Field, the Labour chairman of the Commons social security
committee, accused the government of making a mistake in deciding the
industry should pay for the regulator, instead of the state, saying 'people
will not trust a regulator that is not independent of the industry'.
Employers will have up to 10 years to meet new minimum solvency standards in
full. However, once they begin to take effect, employers whose schemes have
less than 90 per cent of assets needed to pay liabilities will have to add
additional cash almost immediately, a proposal which the industry had
opposed.
The white paper proposes eliminating guaranteed minimum pensions and
substituting a new protection against inflation. It will be required to
increase pensions in payment by 5 per cent or the rate of inflation,
whichever is lower. The white paper proposes linking tax rebates for
personal pension holders to their age and allowing those about to retire
some flexibility in buying an annuity.
Mr Ron Amy, chairman of the National Association of Pension Funds,
criticised the proposal to make schemes pay for the cost of the regulator.
'Regulation should be paid for by the state if - as we believe - it is in
the national interest for pension funds to be regulated effectively.'
Mr Nigel O'Sullivan, partner at consulting actuaries Bacon and Woodrow, said
the role of the regulator was too limited.
Details, Pages 10-11
Editorial Comment, Page 19
Lex, Page 20
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
            Strengthening the industry: The main proposals
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
  New pensions regulator will be funded by a levy on industry,
estimated at Pounds 10m
  Minimum solvency standards take effect in 1997. Schemes will have
five years to meet them, and another three years if they meet at least
90 per cent of the standard. Some may be required to shift investment
from equities to gilts
  Scheme members will have the right to appoint at least one-third of
trustees, with a minimum of one
  Compensation scheme for fraud or misappropriation will be financed
by industry and cover up to 90 per cent of missing assets
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
