<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 94 / MMC warns retailers about misleading CD 'hit' lists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK music industry was yesterday cleared of overcharging for compact
discs, but retailers were told to explain that the charts in their windows
often listed hits they wanted to sell rather than those already sold.
The Monopolies and Mergers Commission, in a long-awaited report on the music
industry, said the way some retailers compiled their music charts was
misleading. The commission found that several retailers, including market
leader WH Smith and its Our Price subsidiary, based their charts on
predicted rather than actual sales.
The commission added: 'We were also concerned to learn that WH Smith had in
the past charged record companies for inclusion in the chart.' It said it
was 'unacceptable to display a chart which might well have the effect of
misleading consumers'.
Mr Neil Hamilton, corporate affairs minister, said yesterday that he had
asked Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, to seek
assurances from retailers that they would specify at the point of display
how their charts had been compiled.
The misleading charts were the only sour note for the music industry in a
report which otherwise acquitted it of overcharging for CDs, an accusation
levelled persistently by the Consumers' Association and by the House of
Commons national heritage committee.
The national heritage committee last year called for a cut of at least
Pounds 2 in the dealer price of CDs. It said the music industry had given no
adequate explanation of why CDs cost less in the US than in the UK.
The Commission said, however, that the price of CDs was determined by what
consumers were prepared to pay. It said that industrialised countries other
than the US generally had higher CD prices than the UK.
The Commission said the CD price differences between the US and the UK
largely resulted from different tax arrangements. Sales taxes in the US were
lower than the UK's 17.5 per cent value added tax rate. Full price popular
CDs were on average only seven to 9 per cent more expensive in the UK than
the US.
The Consumers' Association called the report 'astonishingly complacent'. Mr
Stephen Locke, the association's policy director, said: 'The toothless
watchdog that is the MMC has come up with yet another weak and muddle-headed
report . . .The losers are consumers.'
Music to industry's ears, Page 9
</TEXT>
<XX>
