<DATE>940623
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / International Company News: Kidder gives GE a taste of
turmoil - Securities firm has been beset by speculation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the 13 years that Mr Jack Welch has headed General Electric, he has taken
it into dozens of different businesses. He became one of the most respected
big-company bosses in the US. But none of it prepared him for the whirlwind
that has whipped around Kidder Peabody for the past two months.
'This is the first experience we have in a business where perceptions, which
have no basis in fact, can become reality,' Mr Welch said yesterday.
Kidder has been assailed in recent weeks by incessant speculation about its
financial stability. It claims it was the victim of a large fraud with a big
portfolio of mortgage-backed bonds as bond markets were falling fast - so it
is little surprise there have been questions about its health. On Wall
Street, where financial firms live or die by the strength of their balance
sheets, rumours began to fly.
Other securities firms, lacking a strong parent such as GE, have succumbed
to this death by a thousand cuts. Drexel Burnham Lambert and E. F. Hutton
collapsed in the face of a liquidity crisis as market confidence
disappeared.
Had GE not acted, it could have happened to Kidder. Mr Welch yesterday said
the securities firm had not experienced any funding problems, but it might
have done in time. Like all securities firms, Kidder - with assets of more
than Dollars 100bn at the end of March - relies on the confidence of the
markets.
There were signs that some customers, particularly retail ones, were
deserting, Mr Welch added. 'We didn't have any problems - yet. But it was
going to get worse and worse.'
The management changes at Kidder follow GE's decision to inject Dollars 200m
of new capital in to the firm to plug the gap left by the phantom profits
scheme allegedly set up by Mr Joseph Jett. GE disclosed yesterday that
Kidder has reduced its assets by about Dollars 17bn since the end of March,
to Dollars 90bn, to increase financial flexibility.
Its portfolio of mortgage-backed bonds had been cut to under Dollars 10bn
from Dollars 16bn, Mr Welch added. These securities - bonds whose interest
and principal are backed by the payments on pools of individual mortgage
loans - have aroused the greatest concerns.
A GE analysis last year indicated Kidder could lose as much as Dollars 100m
on these bond holdings if the market moved against it. This was a risk the
company was prepared to take, given the profitability of this part of its
business.
With US interest rates rising since February and bond markets falling, the
losses in mortgage bonds amount to about Dollars 30m. Kidder will report
second-quarter losses after tax of Dollars 25m-Dollars 30m, GE said.
Mr Welch was unequivocal yesterday in his praise of Kidder's mortgage-backed
bonds group for limiting the damage. Led by Mr Mike Vranos, reputedly one of
the highest-paid traders on Wall Street, they had performed like heroes, and
had done better than '99 per cent of GE managers' faced with such difficult
circumstances, Mr Welch said.
Mr Dennis Dammerman, GE's chief financial officer, and Mr Denis Nayden, the
number two at GE Capital, gave no hints yesterday about what they will do at
Kidder.
The firm still faces an investigation into the Jett affair, undertaken by Mr
Gary Lynch, a former head of enforcement of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, and due next month. It also faces an uncertain market - in the
second half of this year, it could make or lose Dollars 50m, said Mr Welch.
</TEXT>
<XX>
