<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / International Company News: Rhone-Poulenc Rorer to take
Dollars 121m charge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Rhone-Poulenc Rorer, the pharmaceuticals company formed when the French
state-owned chemicals company took a majority stake in the US drug
manufacturer, announced last night that second-quarter profits would be
lower than expected and that it would take a restructuring charge of Dollars
121m, or 58 cents a share, in the quarter.
After taking the charge, the company said it will post a 'small loss' in the
quarter.
Excluding the charge, Rhone-Poulenc said it expected earnings of between 50
cents and 55 cents a share - well below Wall Street estimates of 77 cents a
share - because of slower than expected sales.
Rhone-Poulenc also said that the impact of the charge would not be made up
in the second half of the year, which means its full-year earnings will come
in roughly level with last year. In 1993, the company earned Dollars 421.1m,
or Dollars 2.96 a share, on sales of Dollars 4.02bn.
