<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / Clinton drops threat of N Korea sanctions: US agrees to
talks after assurance on N-programme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton yesterday announced that the US had agreed to
high-level talks with North Korea in Geneva next month, after receiving
assurances that Pyongyang would halt its nuclear programme and allow
international inspectors to monitor the freeze.
The announcement followed days of diplomatic uncertainty as the US sought to
verify that the offer relayed by former US president Jimmy Carter last week
from North Korean President Kim Il-sung met the US's conditions.
'Their definition of freeze was the same as ours,' Mr Clinton said.
North Korea had confirmed that it would not attempt to reload its nuclear
reactor nor to reprocess any of the spent nuclear fuel it has unloaded in
recent weeks, Mr Clinton said.
It would also allow the International Atomic Energy Agency to keep
inspectors in the country to verify that the promised freeze was in fact
being carried out.
The US, meanwhile, will suspend its efforts to persuade the United Nations
Security Council to vote for economic sanctions against North Korea.
Mr Clinton said the moves were 'not a solution to the problem but they do
mark a new opportunity to find a solution'.
He hinted at the possibility of economic assistance and normal diplomatic
relations as the US sought 'to give North Korea a way of moving with dignity
into the international community'.
In the days since Mr Carter returned from Pyongyang, US policy has appeared
to be in some disarray. While the White House cautiously sought formal
confirmation from North Korea through the slow channels of diplomatic
communication at the UN, the former president appeared to undercut his
successor's position by announcing on television that the crisis was over
and that the US had abandoned its sanctions drive.
Mr Douglas Hurd, the British foreign secretary, said that the apparent
confusion had been exaggerated.
'I don't see any incoherence about this. We cannot allow North Korea to
manufacture nuclear weapons; that is an absolute. But they don't have to
stop by teatime today,' he said during a visit to Washington yesterday.
In Seoul earlier yesterday, South Korean officials expressed optimism that
an unprecedented summit meeting with North Korea would take place, after
Pyongyang agreed to discuss arrangements.
Korea survey, separate section
</TEXT>
