<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / Society defends insolvency practice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The leading insolvency trade body yesterday defended the practice by which
bankers can appoint as receivers the same firm of accountants they initially
hired to investigate a troubled company.
Critics - including a company director, two accountancy firms and the Royal
Bank of Scotland - have said that there may be a potential conflict of
interest in the arrangement and have called for an independent inquiry.
The Society of Practitioners of Insolvency (SPI) said a consultation
exercise it carried out with the accountancy profession's joint ethics
committee two years ago concluded that the 'overwhelming majority' of those
asked supported the existing position. However, details from the survey
which were submitted to the council of the Institute of Chartered
Accountants in England and Wales last year show that 30 per cent believed
there was a conflict.
The remaining 70 per cent agreed with a carefully-phrased statement in which
they were asked whether they agreed that the conflict for investigating
accountants was 'perceived rather an actual'.
It is believed that one respondent from outside the profession and at least
one accountancy firm called for a ban although there was no question
soliciting this response.
The exercise led to a few minor changes in ethical guidance on insolvency,
including a requirement that investigating accountants made it clear who
they were acting for.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
