<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / World Cup '94: Swiss bank three points in thriller against
Romania
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
In one of the most open and entertaining games of the tournament so far,
Switzerland romped to their first World Cup finals victory for 40 years by
beating the fancied Romanians 4-1 to put themselves in a strong position to
progress to the second phase.
Four points from two matches and a 5-2 aggregate goal edge should be enough
against all but a complete collapse against Colombia next Sunday.
After Switzerland's Alain Sutter - who is heading for Bayern Munich after
the tournament - had a goal disallowed for offside, the Swiss turned up the
heat and there was no doubt about his sensational strike five minutes later
which give his side the lead.
Romania's influential playmaker Georghe Hagi has a tendency to blow hot and
cold, and last night he was distinctly chilly until the 36th minute, when he
curled a spectacular long-range equalizer past Marco Pascolo.
The Swiss came out after the break with more than their supporters' cowbells
ringing. Stephan Chapuisat got the lead back after 52 minutes following a
goal mouth scramble with more than a suspicion of a Swiss handball.
There was just a hint of offside in Adrian Knup's 65 minute third goal, but
nothing could take away from the beauty of Sforza's powerful run and pass to
set it up. Knup got another seven minutes later, deflecting a right-wing
cross from close range.
There was further misery for Romania when substitute Ion Vladoiu, who had
been on the pitch for just four minutes, was sent off for a wild tackle on
Chapuisat.
The result leaves Romania needing at least a draw against the USA next
Sunday to clinch their place in the next round.
</TEXT>
