<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / Dramatic currency surge both mesmerises and horrifies:
Manufacturers fear a decline in profitability
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERARD BAKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Small huddles of Japanese salarymen broke off their early morning journey to
work in central Tokyo to pause outside the numerous banks and brokers whose
shop windows bear the latest electronic news from the financial markets.
They were hoping to catch a glimpse of the moment when their currency hit
the magical figure of parity with the US cent. But if they were mesmerised
by the ascent of the mighty yen their bosses were stunned at the blow to
nascent recovery hopes.
Some thought the drama apocalyptic. 'The abnormally strong yen will not only
damage the Japanese economy which has been gradually recovering but bring
about the collapse of manufacturers in the country,' said Mr Takeshi Nagano,
president of the Japan Federation of Employers Associations (Nikkeiren).
What hurts most is that they had thought it could not get any worse. Last
year corporate Japan expected the yen to hover around the 120 mark, and were
caught on the hop when it stayed below 110. Chastened, this year most have
planned for a dollar/yen rate of 105. Suddenly even that caution starts to
look optimistic.
Only last month equity analysts were forecasting a healthy return to profits
growth this year after a record-breaking four straight years of decline. But
the yen's climb could halt that. According to Nikko Research, each one yen
rise in the yen against the dollar knocks 3.4 per cent off manufacturers'
pre-tax profits.
Some companies have insurance policies in the form of forward hedged yen
positions, but all acknowledged the key test would be whether a 100 yen
dollar proves durable. 'The economy was at a turning point,' said Mr
Hirohiko Okumura, chief economist at Nomura Research Institute, 'but if the
yen stays above 100 the upward trend will be halted and growth could be
flat.'
Robert Feldman, chief economist at Salomon Brothers Asia, thought that
unlikely, as the country's huge trade surplus was at last beginning to
shrink. 'We are in the last stage of yen appreciation, and it's not going to
stay long,' he said.
But Japan's battered manufacturers have been told for years that the yen's
rise cannot go on for ever. On a depressingly historic day for them, many
were beginning to doubt it.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
