<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / International Company News: Nasdaq seeks partners to set up
European exchange
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nasdaq, the US screen-based exchange which is the world's second largest
stock market by turnover, is holding talks with potential partners about
creating a pan-European exchange for small and medium-sized companies.
Mr Joseph Hardiman, Nasdaq president, said the new exchange could be formed
quite quickly, perhaps in the next 12 to 15 months. Nasdaq would seek to be
a minority shareholder, he said.
The potential participants included the European Venture Capital
Association, the UK-based City Group for Smaller Companies and several
European bourses, he said.
Before Nasdaq would commit itself, he said, 'we have to make sure there are
no overwhelming regulatory hurdles and we have to make sure there is a
critical mass of buyers of these securities'.
Mr Hardiman expressed disappointment that the London Stock Exchange had
rebuffed his suggestion that it become a participant. The LSE recently
announced its own plan to promote trading in shares of smaller companies in
the wake of its intended closure of the Unlisted Securities Market in early
1996.
Mr Michael Lawrence, the London exchange's chief executive, said: 'Our
proposals can, and will, be put into action speedily and without undue cost.
The case for a pan-European venture capital market is far from proved.'
Separately, Mr Jean-Francois Theodore, president of the Societe des Bourses
Francaises, confirmed that he is one of the parties in the Nasdaq
discussions.
Should the bourse participate in a pan-European exchange, it too would hope
to hold a minority stake.
The bourse said there was a particular need to provide an exchange for
companies for which the Paris unlisted securities market was inadequate but
for which full listing was not feasible.
'We are hoping to develop jointly a true international securities market,'
Mr Hardiman said, adding that the ability to trade its securities at 'all
hours' might be one of its attractions.
One possibility might include the opportunity for companies listed on the
exchange to be simultaneously listed on Nasdaq, if regulatory and other
requirements could be met.
Such a move would give guarantee companies who list on the new exchange
access to the US capital markets. While Nasdaq attributes much of its growth
to its specialisation in the shares of small, entrepreneurial high-growth
companies, it is not clear that a European version would be equally
successful.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
