<DATE>940623
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / International Company News: Foster's joins Wheelock in China
brewing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT and LOUISE LUCAS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY, HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Foster's, the Australian brewery group, is joining forces with Wheelock, the
Hong Kong-based trading house, to make a push into the brewing business in
China.
The companies yesterday said evaluation of potential projects in the cities
of Tianjin, Wuhan and Chengdu had already started. They will spend a total
of USDollars 1bn over five years, if initial plans are fully implemented.
Foster's already has two joint ventures in Guangdong Province and Shanghai,
and said its own aims fit neatly with Wheelock's strategy, which centres on
the development of five 'regional hubs' - Guangzhou, Shanghai, Wuhan,
Chengdu/Chongqing and Beijing/Tianjin.
In a recent internal reorganisation, Foster's elevated the importance of
Asian markets by creating a new Foster's Asia division. This incorporates
the existing Foster's China interests.
The decision by the Australian brewer to increase its focus on Asian
expansion opportunities comes as Foster's existing UK and North American
interests are suffering from sluggish demand and extremely competitive
conditions.
Yesterday, by contrast, Foster's pointed out that the beer market in China
grew by about 23m hectolitres in 1993, to around 123m hectolitres  - making
it the world's second-largest beer market after the US and easily surpassing
the Australian beer market of 17m hectolitres.
It also pointed out that the Chinese brewing industry remains fragmented,
with more than 800 breweries, only 10 of which produce more than 1m
hectolitres and none more than 2.5m hectolitres.
The move marks Wheelock's first foray into brewing. Mr John Hung, executive
director, said the group had been looking into the brewery business because
of its potential in China, and that Foster's geographical targets - in the
regional hubs of Tianjin, Wuhan and Chengdu - coincide with Wheelock's own
strategic plans for the mainland. Less than 10 per cent of Wheelock's assets
are in China, but there are plans to increase this to a maximum of 20 per
cent.
The venture will marry Foster's brewery skills with Wheelock's China
know-how and expertise in property development expertise.
Mr Hung said: 'Wheelock has always been the party, in any joint venture,
that brings to the table a number of things: local knowledge, financial
strength, corporate muscle in Hong Kong and China connections, and will help
seek sites.'
The market leader is Tsingtao, the local brewer whose shares are traded in
Hong Kong. However, foreign brands are jockeying for market share.
</TEXT>
