<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / Row widens over government intervention in rail dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The row over the extent of government intervention in the rail dispute grew
yesterday as Labour claimed that Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, had
threatened to veto any deal for signal staff that breached the government's
freeze on the public-sector pay bill.
The claim, which came as the second one-day rail strike brought chaos for
travellers, followed a BBC radio interview in which Mr MacGregor appeared to
agree with the interviewer's assertion that he would block any deal he did
not like.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, general secretary of the RMT rail union, said Mr MacGregor's
intervention was 'unhelpful' and made negotiation of a settlement 'much more
difficult'.
Aides of Mr MacGregor said he never used the word veto and his remarks had
been misinterpreted. The row was dismissed by a Downing Street official as a
media invention.
The transport secretary said the government was 'asking Railtrack to
negotiate on the basis of the approach to public-sector pay that the
chancellor set last autumn'. He agreed that he was in regular contact with
Mr Bob Horton, chairman of Railtrack, the state-owned rail infrastructure
company.
Mr Horton said he was being driven by a 'business and commercial imperative'
and he would not 'buy peace' to end the signalling dispute.
About 1,000 trains ran yesterday in spite of the one-day strike. Normally,
about 15,000 trains run each day. They carried few passengers. Travellers
either did not know the services were running or feared they might not be
able to use them to return home.
The rail union said it was alarmed about reports that unqualified managers
had been used to operate the signal boxes.
Mr Knapp has written to the Chief Inspector of Railways, urging him to
investigate the allegations. Citing reports from Rugby, the Trent area,
Shoeburyness and Paisley, he said: 'The possible disastrous implications of
such practices are quite apparent and need no explanation.'
Railtrack said the Health and Safety Executive was content with the
competence checks applied to the staff working yesterday. Union officials
said RMT headquarters were being 'bombarded' with calls from signalling
staff opposed to the company's productivity package, which was rejected by
union negotiators on Monday.
'They are being asked to swallow a huge package of new working practices for
no gain,' a spokesman said. The RMT, which is holding its annual conference
next week, has announced two further 24-hour strikes for Wednesday June 29
and July 6.
Train companies claim compensation, Page 8
</TEXT>
