<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Prokofiev, it seems, believed that his best opera was The Fiery Angel which
he wrote in the early 1920s, though he had to wait 30 years to see it
produced. Performances are still infrequent, and those in the original
Russian very rare. However, Radio 3 provides one of those rare occasions
today with a broadcast of a performance from La Scala, Milan (7.30). It is a
five-act work, about black magic and murder in 16th century Germany. A
predominantly eastern European cast is led by soprano Galina Gorchakova. On
Radio 4 the often excellent Analysis asks whether public scares over matters
such as global warming and toxic waste are rational and why environmental
concerns take precedence over more obvious and immediate hazards (8.00). The
second episode of BBC1's drama Roughnecks, about life on a North Sea oil rig
will show whether this is just another forgettable middlebrow, middleweight
series or whether there is a bit more to it (9.30). In its True Stories slot
C4 shows an over long American home video documentary about living and dying
with Aids (9.30).
</TEXT>
