<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / Sickert nude is sold for Pounds 155,000
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'The Beribboned Washstand', one of the first major nude studies by Walter
Sickert, sold for Pounds 155,000 at Sotheby's yesterday. Painted in 1904 in
Venice it shows a pensive model in a cheap bedroom and sold at the top of
its estimate.
It came from a collection of 16 works by Sickert, and all but two found
buyers, while 'La Bonne Fille' almost doubled its estimate at Pounds
106,500.
'Dockside Cafe, Marseilles', painted by Edward Burra in 1929, and depicting
sailors in a bar, made Pounds 111,500, while 'The Striped Blouse' by Henry
la Thangue sold at the bottom of its estimate for Pounds 84,000.
The auction of 20th-century British art totalled Pounds 1.84m and was 32 per
cent unsold. There were signs that confidence is slowly returning to this
sector of the art market. For example, 'The Green Gate' by Paul Nash found
no takers when Sotheby's offered it at auction last year with a Pounds
20,000 reserve. Yesterday it sold for Pounds 31,050.
</TEXT>
