<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / Council performance varies widely
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Some local authorities in England and Wales promise to answer the telephone
within four seconds - but others are prepared to leave it ringing for a
minute.
Several other examples of widely varying targets for councils are revealed
today by the Audit Commission, the local-government watchdog, in a report
preparing for the compulsory publication of performance indicators this
year.
Targets for answering letters also show inconsistencies. The Isle of Wight
undertakes to answer all letters within three working days. Sunderland aims
for five weeks and Easington, in County Durham, has a target of six weeks
for a full response - although acknowledgements must be sent within seven
working days.
Surrey county council undertakes to answer the telephone within 60 seconds -
although the authority now realises this was unambitious, and will cut the
target to 20 seconds. North Yorkshire expects its staff to answer within
four seconds.
Typical targets are for letters to be answered within 10 days and telephones
within 15 seconds. Councils will have to publish details of how often they
achieve the targets.
Mr Paul Vevers, associate director of the commission, said 93 per cent of
authorities had set targets, which mostly compared well with private-sector
targets - for example, British Gas aims to answer telephone calls within 30
seconds.
He said response times could often be cut with minimal investment in
electronic logging systems for telephones, or extra staff training.
Is Anybody There? Improving Performance in Answering Letters and Telephones,
Audit Commission, HMSO. Pounds 6.
