<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / Political Notebook: Shattered dreams of job security
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Politicians always take time to catch up with the real world. So we should
not be surprised that they are only now beginning to grasp the political
implications of the revolution in Britain's employment market.
Rapid technological advance, deregulation and below-trend economic growth
have created an unnerving new force in society that will shape politics into
the next century.
It is called job insecurity. Its advance into the ranks of the affluent
working and the middle classes marks the end of the post-war life plan: the
reassuring assumption that the employed could rely on an uninterrupted and
steadily rising stream of income throughout their working lives.
Mortgage repayments, comfortable retirement pensions and school fees can no
longer be taken for granted. Long-term employment prospects have replaced
house prices as the favourite topic of conversation around the dining tables
of the tortured middle classes.
The economics have been obvious for some time. As the former chancellor
reminded us in a lecture this week, employment market flexibility was at the
heart of Lord Lawson's supply-side revolution during the 1980s.
The erosion of trade union powers, decentralisation of pay bargaining and
globalisation of markets all pulled in the same direction. So too did the
shifts in business organisation, led by the explosion of information
technology. Government policy and market outcomes have been mutually
reinforcing.
The low paid were the first to be hit. For unskilled workers the hope, let
alone the expectation, of a job for life evaporated in the 1980s. Wages have
been driven down to levels that worry even the most fervent apostles of the
market.
Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, acknowledged this week the
disturbing impact of low pay on family life. Lord Lawson floated the idea of
a large-scale extension of income support payments.
But it is the impact higher up the income scale that has real political
implications. The aspirant classes are discovering that the obverse of
flexibility is insecurity.
The economy's emergence from recession has confirmed the change as
structural rather than cyclical. Short-term employment contracts, part-time
working and early redundancy have become permanent features of the labour
market.
They no longer affect only the poor. The computer manager is as likely as
the contract cleaner to discover his or her job is guaranteed only for the
next two or three years.
The trend is irreversible. A return to fuller employment in the recovery
stage of the economic cycle will not bring with it the security that
post-war generations have taken for granted.
Politicians on left and right have begun to explore the implications. Mr
Kenneth Clarke devoted his recent Mais lecture to the subject. Mr Tony Blair
has made it a theme of his leadership campaign.
Both men set out their goal as full employment. They defined it in terms of
the 1944 white paper: a commitment to a high and stable level of employment.
But politicians have been more comfortable describing what is happening than
offering analysis or prescription.
The Conservatives have the most to lose. The party's political success in
southern England has been based largely on meeting the aspirations of
skilled blue-collar and white-collar workers. Now the market will no longer
deliver. British workers are about to learn the lesson faced by their US
counterparts during the 1980s: there is no longer a guarantee that their
children will have a better standard of living than they have had.
In the US, President George Bush paid the price when Mr Bill Clinton
promised 'managed change'. In Britain the Tories face the same threat. A cut
of 1p in the basic rate of income tax does not have quite the same resonance
for a family wondering how long it can rely on a stable income.
Mr Clarke recognised the danger with a strong defence in his Mais lecture of
the welfare state. He offered a commitment to 'active' labour market
intervention: the education and skills training essential to frequent career
changes.
Mr Blair, though, has the advantage. He will not find solutions in
re-regulation of the employment market or in old-fashioned industrial
interventionism. But the language of individualism has lost its appeal in
the uncertain 1990s.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
