<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / Pledge on Post Office sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is satisfied that privatisation of the Post Office would not
lead to the imposition of value added tax on stamps, trade and industry
minister Mr Patrick McLoughlin told MPs yesterday, David Owen writes.
He said the changes being considered posed no threat to the universal
nationwide tariff structure of the Post Office, nor to the commitment to
maintain a nationwide delivery service. A green paper setting out options
for Royal Mail and Parcelforce, the parcels arm of the Post Office, would be
published shortly.
Mr John Major recently asked Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry
secretary, to redraft the green paper, which was understood to have leaned
heavily in favour of privatising 51 per cent of the Post Office, leaving the
rest in government hands.
Some Tory backbenchers would prefer to leave the Post Office entirely in the
public domain. Ministers are considering whether to include a bill to change
its status in next year's legislative timetable.
While Mr McLoughlin's comments on VAT will reassure backbenchers, they may
worry the private-sector competitors of the Post Office, some of whom are
concerned that the organisation might secure an unfair competitive edge.
Questioned by Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, on what
the government's reaction would be if consultations revealed that most
customers did not want to see the Post Office privatised, Mr McLoughlin said
the government would 'take note' of what was said.
</TEXT>
