FT  23 JUN 94 / Minister defends Pounds 2.2bn aid budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's Pounds 2.2bn overseas aid programme was the sixth largest in the
world and was targeted closely on the needs of developing countries, Mr
Alastair Goodlad, Foreign Office minister, told the Commons last night, Ivor
Owen writes.
He said statistics to be published by the Organisation for Economic
Co-operation and Development would show that UK aid last year was above the
average at 0.31 per cent of gross national product.
Mr Tom Clarke, Labour's shadow overseas aid minister, condemned the link
between British aid and the sale of arms. He cited the Pergau dam project in
Malaysia as an example of the government's failure to target aid on
countries in greatest need.
He said that if appraisal documents had been made public the aid for the dam
would never have been approved.
Sir David Steel, foreign affairs spokesman for the Liberal Democrats, called
for the register of arms sales instituted by the United Nations to be
upgraded into an instrument to control the trade.
He said: 'There is no more appalling hypocrisy in international politics
than seeing the countries in the developed world compete in the sale of arms
to unstable regimes and then stand around wringing our collective hands the
moment they are used.'
