<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 94 / Insurer set up for London buses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London Transport has been forced to set up its own insurance company to
provide affordable cover to the 10 London bus companies which are due to be
privatised later this year.
Dublin-based Routemaster Reinsurance, named after the best-known of London's
red buses, is intended to fill a gap in the insurance market. Mr Clive
Pracy, head of risk management at London Transport, said the company would
allow newly established management buy-out teams, which had no operating
record to put to the insurance industry, to buy insurance at reasonable
rates.
Insurance premiums are expected to be the largest cost item in the bus
companies' accounts after wages.
The move by London Transport will be watched closely by the soon-to-be
privatised train-operating companies which will also face difficulties in
obtaining affordable insurance.
Initially each of the 10 bus operators will become a shareholder in the new
company, although membership could be widened to include bus companies from
other parts of the UK.
The company has been set up with Willis Corroon, an insurance broker, which
will act as manager for Routemaster in the Irish Republic, and with Zurich
Municipal, an insurance company which will provide cover in the UK.
For many years London Transport covered its own insurance risks. In 1991 it
moved to Municipal &amp; Mutual, now the Zurich Municipal, but it still carried
a large 'excess', meeting the first Pounds 250,000 of each claim. Under
Routemaster Reinsurance bus companies will meet only the first Pounds 5,000
of each claim.
</TEXT>
